{"title_page": "John McGeoch", "text_new": "{{for|the American psychologist and educator|John Alexander McGeoch}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = John McGeoch\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = John-McGeoch.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| birth_name          =  John Alexander McGeoch\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|08|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], Scotland\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2004|03|04|1955|08|25|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]], [[Cornwall]], England\n| instrument          = [[Guitar]], [[piano]], [[saxophone]]\n| genre               = [[Post-punk]], [[New wave music|new wave]], [[gothic rock]], [[synthpop]], [[alternative rock]]\n| occupation          = Guitarist\n| years_active        = 1970\u20131995\n| label               = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]], [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], [[Visage (band)|Visage]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[The Armoury Show]], [[Public Image Ltd]], Pacific\n| website             =\n}}\n'''John Alexander McGeoch''' (25 August 1955 \u2013 4 March 2004) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] pop music guitarist who played with several bands of the [[post-punk]] era, including [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Visage (band)|Visage]], and [[Public Image Ltd]].\n\nHe has been described as one of the most influential guitarists of his generation.<ref name=Independent>{{cite news | last = Perrone | first = Pierre | title = Obituary \u2013 John McGeoch: Influential post-punk guitarist | newspaper = [[The Independent]] | date = 2004-03-11 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-549598.html | access-date = 2016-02-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110922001036/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-549598.html | archive-date = 2011-09-22 | quote = Often cited as an influence by leading guitarists such as the Edge from U2, John Frusciante of Red Hot Chili Peppers and Radiohead's Jonny Greenwood, John McGeoch played in several post-punk bands of the late Seventies and early Eighties.}}</ref> In 1996 he was listed by ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' in their \"100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" for his work on the Siouxsie and the Banshees song \"[[Spellbound (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Spellbound]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/mojo.html#guitar | title = Mojo \u2013 100 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time June 1996 Issue | date = 1996 | website = [[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] | access-date = 2016-02-29 | quote = 89. John McGeogh \u2013 Spellbound (Siouxsie & the Banshees, Juju) \u2013 1981 \u2013 Yamaha SG1000 }}</ref> Signature characteristics of his playing style included an inventive [[arpeggio]]s, [[string harmonics]], the uses of [[flanging|flanger]] and an occasional disregard for [[diatonic scale|conventional scales]].\n\nMusician and producer [[Steve Albini]] praised McGeoch for his guitar playing with Magazine and Siouxsie and the Banshees, qualifying as \"great choral swells, great scratches and buzzes, great dissonant noise and great squealy death noise What a guy\" and further commenting: \"anybody can make notes. There's no trick. What is a trick and a good one is to make a guitar do things that don't sound like a guitar at all. The point here is stretching the boundaries\".<ref>[[Steve Albini]]. (September \u2013 October 1984). \"Tired of Ugy Fat ?\". ''Matter [a Music Magazine]'' (10).</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcGeoch was born on 25 August 1955 in [[Greenock]], [[Renfrewshire]], [[Scotland]], where he spent his childhood years. He began to play the guitar at 12 years of age, first learning [[British blues]] music, being influenced by the work of [[Eric Clapton]], and also that of [[Jimi Hendrix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armouryshow.com/media/interviews/1985-11-00_The_Guitarist-John_mcgeoch_03.jpg |title=Interview|website=Armourshow.com |accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref> In 1970 he played with a local band called the 'Slugband'. In 1971 his parents moved to London. In 1975 he went to [[Manchester Polytechnic]] where he received a degree in Fine Art. He maintained an interest in photography, painting and drawing throughout his life.\n\n==Early career==\nIn April 1977 McGeoch's Manchester student flatmate [[Malcolm Garrett]] introduced him to [[Howard Devoto]], who had recently left the [[Buzzcocks]] and was looking for a guitarist to form a band with. The pair formed a new act entitled [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], along with [[Barry Adamson]], Bob Dickinson and [[Martin Jackson]]. The new band released its debut single, \"[[Shot by Both Sides]]\" in January 1978. The song's music was written by [[Pete Shelley]] with new Devoto lyrics (the Buzzcocks version was titled \"Lipstick\"); on release it reached #41 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. (The same year McGeoch graduated from Manchester Polytechnic) .\n\nMcGeoch went on to play on Magazine's first three albums, ''[[Real Life (Magazine album)|Real Life]]'' (1978), ''[[Secondhand Daylight]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]'' (1980). He left the band in 1980 shortly after the release of the latter album, frustrated with its lack of commercial success despite its recognition with music press critics.\n\nIn 1979, while still a member of Magazine, McGeoch joined [[Steve Strange]]'s electronic band [[Visage (band)|Visage]] along with erstwhile Magazine bandmates Adamson and [[Dave Formula]], recording songs for their first single \"[[Tar (song)|Tar]]\" and later, in 1980, for their eponymous album ''[[Visage (Visage album)|Visage]]'', McGeoch playing guitar and saxophone on the record.\n\nAlthough he saw Visage as something of a joke,<ref name=\"Simpson\">{{Cite news |title= Obituary \u2013 John McGeoch: Innovative and influential guitarist of the post-punk era|newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 March 2004 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries | first=Dave | last=Simpson | accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> the band provided McGeoch with early professional credibility and success. The band's single \"[[Fade to Grey (Visage song)|Fade to Grey]]\" went to #1 in a number of European countries. McGeoch did not record on the group's second album, ''[[The Anvil (album)|The Anvil]]'', as it was recorded in London and he was unable to participate.\n\nWhile still a member of Magazine and Visage, McGeoch also worked occasionally with other bands. In mid-1980 he recorded most of the guitar work on [[Generation X (band)|Gen X]]'s album ''[[Kiss Me Deadly (album)|Kiss Me Deadly]]'' at [[AIR Studios]] in London.<ref>'Dancing with Myself', by Billy Idol. (Pub. Simon & Schuster, 2014).</ref> In September 1980 he guested with the [[Skids (band)|Skids]] for a [[Peel Session]], standing in for [[Stuart Adamson]] who was unwell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/sessions/1980s/1980/Sep01skids|title=BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Keeping It Peel \u2013 01/09/1980 Skids|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> He also collaborated with ex-Magazine drummer [[John Doyle (drummer)|John Doyle]] on [[Ken Lockie]]'s album ''[[The Impossible (album)|The Impossible]]'' (1981). Around this time, he left Magazine.\n\n==Siouxsie and the Banshees==\nAfter joining [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]] in late 1980,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1456851/John-McGeoch.html \"Obituary , John McGeoch\"]. Telegraph.co.uk. 15 March 2004.</ref> McGeoch entered a period of both creative and commercial success. During his first session with the Banshees he began a new style of playing. He later commented: \"I was going through a picky phase, as opposed to strumming. \"Happy House\" was lighter and had more musicality in it. They invited me to join. I was sad leaving Magazine but the Banshees were so interesting and it felt like a good move\".<ref name=Independent />\n\nHe recorded guitar on the Banshees' long-players ''[[Kaleidoscope (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (1980), ''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]'' (1981) and ''[[A Kiss in the Dreamhouse]]'' (1982). The Banshees' hit singles of this era featured some of McGeoch's most acclaimed work, particularly 1980's \"[[Happy House]]\", \"[[Christine (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Christine]]\" and \"[[Israel (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Israel]]\", and 1981's \"[[Spellbound (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Spellbound]]\" and \"[[Arabian Knights (song)|Arabian Knights]]\". McGeoch's contribution to the band was important in terms of sounds and style. Singer [[Siouxsie Sioux]] later said: {{Cquote|John McGeoch was my favourite guitarist of all time. He was into sound in an almost abstract way. I loved the fact that I could say, \"I want this to sound like a horse falling off a cliff\", and he would know exactly what I meant. He was easily, without a shadow of a doubt, the most creative guitarist the Banshees ever had\".<ref name=Independent />}} However, McGeoch suffered a [[nervous breakdown]] due to the stresses of touring and an increasing personal problem with alcohol, and after collapsing on stage during a performance at a gig in [[Madrid]], left the band in 1982.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/>\n\n==Later career==\nIn 1983, during a break from playing music, he produced Swedish punk-funk band ''Zzzang Tumb's'' debut long-player.<ref name=\"Black Mat Smith\">{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Black Mat|title=Happy Talk|url=http://www.fodderstompf.com/ARCHIVES/INTERVIEWS/mm87.html|work=Fodderstompf|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986 McGeoch contributed to former [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]] singer [[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]]'s debut solo long-player ''[[Should the World Fail to Fall Apart]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Pierre Perrone |title=John McGeoch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-38149.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=2 July 2018 |format=Obituary |date=11 March 2004}}</ref>\n\nFollowing three years playing guitar with an act entitled [[The Armoury Show]] (which included Doyle as well as ex-Skids members [[Richard Jobson (television presenter)|Richard Jobson]] and [[Russell Webb (musician)|Russell Webb]]), the album Waiting For the floods features some of his best guitar work. McGeoch joined [[John Lydon]]'s [[Public Image Ltd]] in 1986, a decision which may have been partly motivated by financial difficulties he was in at this time. He had been an admirer of PiL, particularly of Lydon's song-lyrics, yet reportedly had previously turned down an offer from him to join the band in 1984. Despite being struck in the face with a bottle thrown from the crowd during one of his first gigs with the band, McGeoch remained with PiL until it disbanded in 1992, making him the longest-serving member apart from Lydon. He recorded on its long-players: ''[[Happy? (Public Image Limited)|Happy?]]'', ''[[9 (Public Image Limited album)|9]]'' and ''[[That What Is Not]]''. McGeoch left PiL's line-up in 1992.\n\nIn 1992 he was invited by the Icelandic band [[The Sugarcubes]] to play the guitar track on the song \"Gold\" for their ''[[Stick Around for Joy]]'' long-player. In early 1990s, without a band, he ended his career seeking to form one via a variety of short-lived ventures, including working with [[Glenn Gregory]] and the songwriter/producer Keith Lowndes. With [[John Keeble]] of [[Spandau Ballet]] and vocalist Clive Farrington of [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]], he formed a line-up provisionally titled 'Pacific', but no commercial material came of it.\n\nIn the mid-1990s McGeoch retired from professional music and trained mid-life as a nurse/carer. In the early 2000s he was reported as attempting to re-enter professional music by working on musical scores for television productions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504100128/http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries |archive-date=4 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMcGeoch died at the age of 48 in his sleep on 4 March 2004 at his home in [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]], [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Simpson\"/>\n\n==Tributes==\nBanshees' drummer [[Budgie (musician)|Budgie]] wrote a text to honour him on the Siouxsie website, saying: \"Without any disrespect to all the other guitarists we have worked with, none had the relaxed mastery and such a depth of expression as John McGeoch. No amount of scrutiny of filmed 'Live' performance tapes could reveal the subtle economy of technique that made an apparently complex phrase look so deceptively simple. Exasperated guitarists would often comment, \"But his hands don\u2019t even move!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecreatures.com/creatures/?view=94&offset=0&length=5 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606174449/http://www.thecreatures.com/creatures/?view=94&offset=0&length=5 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 June 2004 |title=Some Words for John |publisher=Thecreatures.com |date=11 March 2003 |accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 9 September 1981 he married Janet Pickford, his girlfriend at Manchester Polytechnic, the marriage later being divorced.<ref>\"England and Wales Marriage Registration Index, 1837\u20132005,\" database, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVX8-Q9GV : 8 October 2014), John A Mcgeoch and null, 1981; from \"England & Wales Marriages, 1837\u20132005\", database, findmypast (http://www.findmypast.com : 2012); citing 1981, quarter 3, vol. 13, p. 1563, Islington, London, England, General Register Office, Southport, England.</ref> On 14 September 1988 McGeoch married Denise Dakin,<ref>Gregory, Andy. \"The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002\", p. 233. Published by Routledge, 2002. {{ISBN|1-85743-161-8}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85743-161-2}}</ref> the second marriage producing a daughter, Emily Jean McGeoch (b. 1989).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myspace.com/j_mcgeoch |title=John McGeoch RIP (j_mcgeoch) on Myspace |website=Myspace.com |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/14723651138/?ref=ts&fref=ts |title=Facebook |website=Facebook.com |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nMcGeoch has been cited by many artists as a major influence. [[Johnny Marr]] from [[the Smiths]] hailed him, saying: \"Really my generation was all about a guy called John McGeoch, from Siouxsie and the Banshees\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/entertainment/music/article/Johnny-Marr-talks-about-making-his-own-music-13279599.php|title=Johnny Marr talks about making his own music|website=Houstonchronicle.com|first=Andrew |last=Dansby |date=4 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004172854/https://www.houstonchronicle.com/entertainment/music/article/Johnny-Marr-talks-about-making-his-own-music-13279599.php |archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"When I was in my teens, there weren't many new guitar players who were interesting and of their time.[...] John McGeoch. [His work] was really innovative guitar music which was pretty hard to find back then. To a young guitar player like myself, those early Banshees singles were just class\".<ref name=Goddard>{{cite book |author=Goddard, Simon |title=Mozipedia: The Encyclopaedia of Morrissey and the Smiths [Sioux, Siouxsie entry] |publisher=Ebury Press |page= 393}}</ref> [[Simon Goddard]] wrote that McGeoch was a \"significant inspiration\" on Marr.<ref name=Goddard  />\n\n[[Radiohead]]'s [[Ed O'Brien]] cited him as a \"big influence\", citing him as one of the \"great guitarists, but they weren\u2019t lead guitarists\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/radioheads-ed-obrien-i-was-always-drawn-to-sounds-that-didnt-sound-like-the-guitar\n|title=Radiohead\u2019s Ed O\u2019Brien: \"I was always drawn to sounds that didn\u2019t sound like the guitar |website=MusicRadar.com |date=14 November 2017 |author=Michael Astley-Brown, Rob Laing |accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> Radiohead were also inspired by McGeoch to record \"There There\". They explained that they were \"in heaven\" when their producer [[Nigel Godrich]] made [[Jonny Greenwood]] sound like Siouxsie and the Banshees-era McGeoch for that session.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolmusic.ca/artist_page.asp?artist_id=1154 |title=Radiohead Biography capitolmusic.ca |accessdate=2009-02-17 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629064700/http://www.capitolmusic.ca/artist_page.asp?artist_id=1154 |archivedate=29 June 2006 }} Excerpt. Colin Greenwood remembers: \"The running joke when we were making this record was that if we recorded a track that stretched over 3mn 50 sec., we'd say \"Oh fuck, we've buggered it then. It's gone on too long.\" Of course, the irony is that the first single we're releasing is actually the longest song on the record. (\"There There\"). It was all recorded live in Oxford. We all got excited at the end because Nigel was trying to get Jonny to play like John McGeoch in Siouxsie and the Banshees. All the old farts in the band were in seventh heaven.\"\n</ref> U2's \"[[The Edge]]\" has cited McGeoch as an influence, and chose the Siouxsie and the Banshees song \"Christine\" from the ''Kaleidoscope'' album for a compilation made for ''Mojo''.<ref>[http://www.u2wanderer.org/disco/odd010.html \"U2 Jukebox\"] U2wanderer.org. U2'Compilation for Mojo Magazine featuring \"Christine\"</ref>\n\nOther guitarists also mentioned him. [[Dave Navarro]] of [[Jane's Addiction]] said that he learned guitar by listening to the albums McGeoch recorded with Siouxsie and the Banshees.<ref>Paytress, Mark. ''Siouxsie & the Banshees: The Authorised Biography''. Sanctuary, 2003. {{ISBN|1-86074-375-7}}</ref> [[John Frusciante]] of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] named McGeoch in his primary influences: \"[McGeoch] is such a guitarist I aspire to be. He has a new brilliant idea for each song. I usually play on the stuff he does on Magazine's albums and Siouxsie & the Banshees's like ''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]''\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Tore S Borjesson |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/musik/article10360246.ab |title=Red Hots verkliga frontman John Frusciante |newspaper=Aftonbladet |date=24 April 2003 |accessdate=2 July 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703193605/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/musik/article10360246.ab |archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the BBC aired an hour-long radio documentary on McGeoch's life and work, titled ''Spellbound: The John McGeoch Story''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAoLW3Mdt4o |title='Spellbound: The John McGeoch Story' \u2013 hour-long BBC radio documentary |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\nDuring his time with Magazine McGeoch played a [[Yamaha Corporation|Yamaha]] SG1000 guitar with a stand-mounted [[MXR]] M117R [[flanging|flanger]].<ref>[http://www.wire-sound.com/2008/12/12/noko-ipso-facto-devoto/ Wire-sound.com, ''Magazine'', 12/12/2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221042437/http://www.wire-sound.com/2008/12/12/noko-ipso-facto-devoto/ |date=21 February 2009 }}''With Magazine, McGeoch played a Yamaha SG1000 + MXR Flanger + a few other bits.''</ref> He bought his first model in 1977 when the band signed its recording deal, which provided him with the finances for professional standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armouryshow.com/media/interviews/1985-11-00_The_Guitarist-John_mcgeoch_01.jpg |title=Interview |website=Armourshow.com |accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref> Whilst with Siouxsie and the Banshees he created his own setup, involving an MXR flanger mounted on a mic stand which allowed him to hit a chord and sweep the flange knob in real time.<ref>\"The Gothfather\" [Robert Smith of the Cure interview]. Guitar Word. June 1996</ref> Whilst working with 'The Armoury Show', he also used a [[Squier Stratocaster|Squier 1957 Stratocaster]] and an [[Ibanez]] AE410BK. During his work with PiL, and in his last years he favoured a solid wood [[Carvin Corporation|Carvin]] electric guitar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://equipboard.com/pros/john-mcgeoch/carvin-dc400-electric-guitar|title=John McGeoch's Carvin DC400 Electric Guitar|website=Equipboard.com|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> He also used a [[Washburn Guitars|Washburn]] Tour 24 guitar for touring during 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5UGUjs_7cPA|title=Public Image Ltd.- Glasnost Rock- Rock Summer 1988|last=Miguel Martinez|date=8 January 2013|accessdate=28 April 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n;Magazine\n*''[[Real Life (Magazine album)|Real Life]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Secondhand Daylight]]'' (1979)\n*''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]'' (1980)\n;Visage\n*''[[Visage (Visage album)|Visage]]'' (1980)\n;Gen X\n*''[[Kiss Me Deadly (album)|Kiss Me Deadly]]'' (1981)\n;Siouxsie and the Banshees\n*''[[Kaleidoscope (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]'' (1981)\n*''[[A Kiss in the Dreamhouse]]'' (1982)\n;The Armoury Show\n*''[[Waiting for the Floods]]'' (1985)\n;Peter Murphy\n*''[[Should the World Fail to Fall Apart]]'' (1986)\n;Public Image Ltd\n*''[[Happy? (Public Image Ltd. album)|Happy?]]'' (1987)\n*''[[9 (Public Image Ltd. album)|9]]'' (1989)\n*''[[That What Is Not]]'' (1992)\n;The Sugarcubes\n*''[[Stick Around for Joy]]'' (1992)\n\n==See also==\n*[[John Doyle (drummer)|John Doyle]]\n*[[Russell Webb (musician)|Russell Webb]]\n*[[Slik]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fodderstompf.com/MEMBERS/mcgeoch.html Fodderstompf.Com: John McGeoch Biography]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/j_mcgeoch John McGeoch MySpace Account (set up by his daughter)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051215185737/http://shotbybothsides.com/mag_john.htm Profile of John McGeoch from shotbybothsides.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060102232625/http://shotbybothsides.com/zig_0284.htm Interview with John McGeoch from shotbybothsides.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051215000007/http://america.net/~davdmock/armoury1.htm Interview with John McGeoch and Richard Jobson of Armoury Show]\n\n{{Magazine (band)}}\n{{Siouxsie and the Banshees}}\n{{Public Image Ltd}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGeoch, John}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Magazine (band) members]]\n[[Category:Siouxsie and the Banshees members]]\n[[Category:Public Image Ltd members]]\n[[Category:The Armoury Show members]]\n[[Category:Gothic rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Greenock]]\n[[Category:20th-century guitarists]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the American psychologist and educator|John Alexander McGeoch}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox musical artist  <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name                = John McGeoch\n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| image               = John-McGeoch.jpg\n| image_size          = \n| birth_name          =  John Alexander McGeoch\n| alias               =\n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1955|08|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place         = [[Greenock]], [[Inverclyde]], Scotland\n| death_date          = {{death date and age|2004|03|04|1955|08|25|df=y}}\n| death_place         = [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]], [[Cornwall]], England\n| instrument          = [[Guitar]], [[piano]], [[saxophone]]\n| genre               = [[Post-punk]], [[New wave music|new wave]], [[gothic rock]], [[synthpop]], [[alternative rock]]\n| occupation          = Guitarist\n| years_active        = 1970\u20131995\n| label               = [[Polydor Records|Polydor]], [[Geffen Records|Geffen]]\n| associated_acts     = [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], [[Visage (band)|Visage]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[The Armoury Show]], [[Public Image Ltd]], Pacific\n| website             =\n}}\n'''John Alexander McGeoch''' (25 August 1955 \u2013 4 March 2004) was a [[Scottish people|Scottish]] pop music guitarist who played with several bands of the [[post-punk]] era, including [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]], [[Visage (band)|Visage]], and [[Public Image Ltd]].\n\nHe has been described as one of the most influential guitarists of his generation.<ref name=Independent>{{cite news | last = Perrone | first = Pierre | title = Obituary \u2013 John McGeoch: Influential post-punk guitarist | newspaper = [[The Independent]] | date = 2004-03-11 | url = https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-549598.html | access-date = 2016-02-29 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110922001036/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-549598.html | archive-date = 2011-09-22 | quote = Often cited as an influence by leading guitarists such as the Edge from U2, John Frusciante of Red Hot Chili Peppers and Radiohead's Jonny Greenwood, John McGeoch played in several post-punk bands of the late Seventies and early Eighties.}}</ref> In 1996 he was listed by ''[[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]]'' in their \"100 Greatest Guitarists of All Time\" for his work on the Siouxsie and the Banshees song \"[[Spellbound (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Spellbound]]\".<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rocklistmusic.co.uk/mojo.html#guitar | title = Mojo \u2013 100 Greatest Guitarists Of All Time June 1996 Issue | date = 1996 | website = [[Mojo (magazine)|Mojo]] | access-date = 2016-02-29 | quote = 89. John McGeogh \u2013 Spellbound (Siouxsie & the Banshees, Juju) \u2013 1981 \u2013 Yamaha SG1000 }}</ref> Signature characteristics of his playing style included an inventive [[arpeggio]]s, [[string harmonics]], the uses of [[flanging|flanger]] and an occasional disregard for [[diatonic scale|conventional scales]].\n\nMusician and producer [[Steve Albini]] praised McGeoch for his guitar playing with Magazine and Siouxsie and the Banshees, qualifying as \"great choral swells, great scratches and buzzes, great dissonant noise and great squealy death noise What a guy\" and further commenting: \"anybody can make notes. There's no trick. What is a trick and a good one is to make a guitar do things that don't sound like a guitar at all. The point here is stretching the boundaries\".<ref>[[Steve Albini]]. (September \u2013 October 1984). \"Tired of Ugy Fat ?\". ''Matter [a Music Magazine]'' (10).</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nMcGeoch was born on 25 August 1955 in [[Greenock]], [[Renfrewshire]], [[Scotland]], where he spent his childhood years. He began to play the guitar at 12 years of age, first learning [[British blues]] music, being influenced by the work of [[Eric Clapton]], and also that of [[Jimi Hendrix]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armouryshow.com/media/interviews/1985-11-00_The_Guitarist-John_mcgeoch_03.jpg |title=Interview|website=Armourshow.com |accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref> In 1970 he played with a local band called the 'Slugband'. In 1971 his parents moved to London. In 1975 he went to [[Manchester Polytechnic]] where he received a degree in Fine Art. He maintained an interest in photography, painting and drawing throughout his life.\n\n==Early career==\nIn April 1977 McGeoch's Manchester student flatmate [[Malcolm Garrett]] introduced him to [[Howard Devoto]], who had recently left the [[Buzzcocks]] and was looking for a guitarist to form a band with. The pair formed a new act entitled [[Magazine (band)|Magazine]], along with [[Barry Adamson]], Bob Dickinson and [[Martin Jackson]]. The new band released its debut single, \"[[Shot by Both Sides]]\" in January 1978. The song's music was written by [[Pete Shelley]] with new Devoto lyrics (the Buzzcocks version was titled \"Lipstick\"); on release it reached #41 on the [[UK Singles Chart]]. (The same year McGeoch graduated from Manchester Polytechnic) .\n\nMcGeoch went on to play on Magazine's first three albums, ''[[Real Life (Magazine album)|Real Life]]'' (1978), ''[[Secondhand Daylight]]'' (1979) and ''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]'' (1980). He left the band in 1980 shortly after the release of the latter album, frustrated with its lack of commercial success despite its recognition with music press critics.\n\nIn 1979, while still a member of Magazine, McGeoch joined [[Steve Strange]]'s electronic band [[Visage (band)|Visage]] along with erstwhile Magazine bandmates Adamson and [[Dave Formula]], recording songs for their first single \"[[Tar (song)|Tar]]\" and later, in 1980, for their eponymous album ''[[Visage (Visage album)|Visage]]'', McGeoch playing guitar and saxophone on the record.\n\nAlthough he saw Visage as something of a joke,<ref name=\"Simpson\">{{Cite news |title= Obituary \u2013 John McGeoch: Innovative and influential guitarist of the post-punk era|newspaper=The Guardian |date=12 March 2004 |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries | first=Dave | last=Simpson | accessdate=7 May 2010}}</ref> the band provided McGeoch with early professional credibility and success. The band's single \"[[Fade to Grey (Visage song)|Fade to Grey]]\" went to #1 in a number of European countries. McGeoch did not record on the group's second album, ''[[The Anvil (album)|The Anvil]]'', as it was recorded in London and he was unable to participate.\n\nWhile still a member of Magazine and Visage, McGeoch also worked occasionally with other bands. In mid-1980 he recorded most of the guitar work on [[Generation X (band)|Gen X]]'s album ''[[Kiss Me Deadly (album)|Kiss Me Deadly]]'' at [[AIR Studios]] in London.<ref>'Dancing with Myself', by Billy Idol. (Pub. Simon & Schuster, 2014).</ref> In September 1980 he guested with the [[Skids (band)|Skids]] for a [[Peel Session]], standing in for [[Stuart Adamson]] who was unwell.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/radio1/johnpeel/sessions/1980s/1980/Sep01skids|title=BBC \u2013 Radio 1 \u2013 Keeping It Peel \u2013 01/09/1980 Skids|website=Bbc.co.uk|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> He also collaborated with ex-Magazine drummer [[John Doyle (drummer)|John Doyle]] on [[Ken Lockie]]'s album ''[[The Impossible (album)|The Impossible]]'' (1981). Around this time, he left Magazine.\n\n==Siouxsie and the Banshees==\nAfter joining [[Siouxsie and the Banshees]] in late 1980,<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/1456851/John-McGeoch.html \"Obituary , John McGeoch\"]. Telegraph.co.uk. 15 March 2004.</ref> McGeoch entered a period of both creative and commercial success. During his first session with the Banshees he began a new style of playing. He later commented: \"I was going through a picky phase, as opposed to strumming. \"Happy House\" was lighter and had more musicality in it. They invited me to join. I was sad leaving Magazine but the Banshees were so interesting and it felt like a good move\".<ref name=Independent />\n\nHe recorded guitar on the Banshees' long-players ''[[Kaleidoscope (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (1980), ''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]'' (1981) and ''[[A Kiss in the Dreamhouse]]'' (1982). The Banshees' hit singles of this era featured some of McGeoch's most acclaimed work, particularly 1980's \"[[Happy House]]\", \"[[Christine (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Christine]]\" and \"[[Israel (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Israel]]\", and 1981's \"[[Spellbound (Siouxsie and the Banshees song)|Spellbound]]\" and \"[[Arabian Knights (song)|Arabian Knights]]\". McGeoch's contribution to the band was important in terms of sounds and style. Singer [[Siouxsie Sioux]] later said: {{Cquote|John McGeoch was my favourite guitarist of all time. He was into sound in an almost abstract way. I loved the fact that I could say, \"I want this to sound like a horse falling off a cliff\", and he would know exactly what I meant. He was easily, without a shadow of a doubt, the most creative guitarist the Banshees ever had\".<ref name=Independent />}} However, McGeoch suffered a [[nervous breakdown]] due to the stresses of touring and an increasing personal problem with alcohol, and after collapsing on stage during a performance at a gig in [[Madrid]], left the band in 1982.<ref name=\"Simpson\"/>\n\n==Later career==\nIn 1983, during a break from playing music, he produced Swedish punk-funk band ''Zzzang Tumb's'' debut long-player.<ref name=\"Black Mat Smith\">{{cite web|last=Smith|first=Black Mat|title=Happy Talk|url=http://www.fodderstompf.com/ARCHIVES/INTERVIEWS/mm87.html|work=Fodderstompf|publisher=[[Melody Maker]]|accessdate=16 July 2013}}</ref>\n\nIn 1986 McGeoch contributed to former [[Bauhaus (band)|Bauhaus]] singer [[Peter Murphy (musician)|Peter Murphy]]'s debut solo long-player ''[[Should the World Fail to Fall Apart]]''.<ref>{{cite news |author1=Pierre Perrone |title=John McGeoch |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/obituaries/john-mcgeoch-38149.html |newspaper=[[The Independent]]|accessdate=2 July 2018 |format=Obituary |date=11 March 2004}}</ref>\n\nFollowing three years playing guitar with an act entitled [[The Armoury Show]] (which included Doyle as well as ex-Skids members [[Richard Jobson (television presenter)|Richard Jobson]] and [[Russell Webb (musician)|Russell Webb]]), the album Waiting For the floods features some of his best guitar work. McGeoch joined [[John Lydon]]'s [[Public Image Ltd]] in 1986, a decision which may have been partly motivated by financial difficulties he was in at this time. He had been an admirer of PiL, particularly of Lydon's song-lyrics, yet reportedly had previously turned down an offer from him to join the band in 1984. Despite being struck in the face with a bottle thrown from the crowd during one of his first gigs with the band, McGeoch remained with PiL until it disbanded in 1992, making him the longest-serving member apart from Lydon. He recorded on its long-players: ''[[Happy? (Public Image Limited)|Happy?]]'', ''[[9 (Public Image Limited album)|9]]'' and ''[[That What Is Not]]''. McGeoch left PiL's line-up in 1992.\n\nIn 1992 he was invited by the Icelandic band [[The Sugarcubes]] to play the guitar track on the song \"Gold\" for their ''[[Stick Around for Joy]]'' long-player. In early 1990s, without a band, he ended his career seeking to form one via a variety of short-lived ventures, including working with [[Glenn Gregory]] and the songwriter/producer Keith Lowndes. With [[John Keeble]] of [[Spandau Ballet]] and vocalist Clive Farrington of [[When in Rome (band)|When in Rome]], he formed a line-up provisionally titled 'Pacific', but no commercial material came of it.\n\nIn the mid-1990s McGeoch retired from professional music and trained mid-life as a nurse/carer. In the early 2000s he was reported as attempting to re-enter professional music by working on musical scores for television productions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries |title=Archived copy |access-date=15 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130504100128/http://www.guardian.co.uk/news/2004/mar/12/guardianobituaries.artsobituaries |archive-date=4 May 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nMcGeoch died at the age of 48 in his sleep on 4 March 2004 at his home in [[Launceston, Cornwall|Launceston]], [[Cornwall]].<ref name=\"Simpson\"/>\n\n==Tributes==\nBanshees' drummer [[Budgie (musician)|Budgie]] wrote a text to honour him on the Siouxsie website, saying: \"Without any disrespect to all the other guitarists we have worked with, none had the relaxed mastery and such a depth of expression as John McGeoch. No amount of scrutiny of filmed 'Live' performance tapes could reveal the subtle economy of technique that made an apparently complex phrase look so deceptively simple. Exasperated guitarists would often comment, \"But his hands don\u2019t even move!\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thecreatures.com/creatures/?view=94&offset=0&length=5 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20040606174449/http://www.thecreatures.com/creatures/?view=94&offset=0&length=5 |url-status=dead |archive-date=6 June 2004 |title=Some Words for John |publisher=Thecreatures.com |date=11 March 2003 |accessdate=2 July 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nOn 9 September 1981 he married Janet Pickford, his girlfriend at Manchester Polytechnic, the marriage later being divorced.<ref>\"England and Wales Marriage Registration Index, 1837\u20132005,\" database, FamilySearch (https://familysearch.org/ark:/61903/1:1:QVX8-Q9GV : 8 October 2014), John A Mcgeoch and null, 1981; from \"England & Wales Marriages, 1837\u20132005\", database, findmypast (http://www.findmypast.com : 2012); citing 1981, quarter 3, vol. 13, p. 1563, Islington, London, England, General Register Office, Southport, England.</ref> On 14 September 1988 McGeoch married Denise Dakin,<ref>Gregory, Andy. \"The International Who's Who in Popular Music 2002\", p. 233. Published by Routledge, 2002. {{ISBN|1-85743-161-8}}, {{ISBN|978-1-85743-161-2}}</ref> the second marriage producing a daughter, Emily Jean McGeoch (b. 1989).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://myspace.com/j_mcgeoch |title=John McGeoch RIP (j_mcgeoch) on Myspace |website=Myspace.com |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/groups/14723651138/?ref=ts&fref=ts |title=Facebook |website=Facebook.com |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Influence==\nMcGeoch has been cited by many artists as a major influence. [[Johnny Marr]] from [[the Smiths]] hailed him, saying: \"Really my generation was all about a guy called John McGeoch, from Siouxsie and the Banshees\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.houstonchronicle.com/entertainment/music/article/Johnny-Marr-talks-about-making-his-own-music-13279599.php|title=Johnny Marr talks about making his own music|website=Houstonchronicle.com|first=Andrew |last=Dansby |date=4 October 2018|accessdate=1 November 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181004172854/https://www.houstonchronicle.com/entertainment/music/article/Johnny-Marr-talks-about-making-his-own-music-13279599.php |archivedate=4 October 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> \"When I was in my teens, there weren't many new guitar players who were interesting and of their time.[...] John McGeoch. [His work] was really innovative guitar music which was pretty hard to find back then. To a young guitar player like myself, those early Banshees singles were just class\".<ref name=Goddard>{{cite book |author=Goddard, Simon |title=Mozipedia: The Encyclopaedia of Morrissey and the Smiths [Sioux, Siouxsie entry] |publisher=Ebury Press |page= 393}}</ref> [[Simon Goddard]] wrote that McGeoch was a \"significant inspiration\" on Marr.<ref name=Goddard  />\n\n[[Radiohead]]'s [[Ed O'Brien]] cited him as a \"big influence\", citing him as one of the \"great guitarists, but they weren\u2019t lead guitarists\".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.musicradar.com/news/radioheads-ed-obrien-i-was-always-drawn-to-sounds-that-didnt-sound-like-the-guitar\n|title=Radiohead\u2019s Ed O\u2019Brien: \"I was always drawn to sounds that didn\u2019t sound like the guitar |website=MusicRadar.com |date=14 November 2017 |author=Michael Astley-Brown, Rob Laing |accessdate=19 November 2017}}</ref> Radiohead were also inspired by McGeoch to record \"There There\". They explained that they were \"in heaven\" when their producer [[Nigel Godrich]] made [[Jonny Greenwood]] sound like Siouxsie and the Banshees-era McGeoch for that session.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.capitolmusic.ca/artist_page.asp?artist_id=1154 |title=Radiohead Biography capitolmusic.ca |accessdate=2009-02-17 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060629064700/http://www.capitolmusic.ca/artist_page.asp?artist_id=1154 |archivedate=29 June 2006 }} Excerpt. Colin Greenwood remembers: \"The running joke when we were making this record was that if we recorded a track that stretched over 3mn 50 sec., we'd say \"Oh fuck, we've buggered it then. It's gone on too long.\" Of course, the irony is that the first single we're releasing is actually the longest song on the record. (\"There There\"). It was all recorded live in Oxford. We all got excited at the end because Nigel was trying to get Jonny to play like John McGeoch in Siouxsie and the Banshees. All the old farts in the band were in seventh heaven.\"\n</ref> U2's \"[[The Edge]]\" has cited McGeoch as an influence, and chose the Siouxsie and the Banshees song \"Christine\" from the ''Kaleidoscope'' album for a compilation made for ''Mojo''.<ref>[http://www.u2wanderer.org/disco/odd010.html \"U2 Jukebox\"] U2wanderer.org. U2'Compilation for Mojo Magazine featuring \"Christine\"</ref>\n\nOther guitarists also mentioned him. [[Dave Navarro]] of [[Jane's Addiction]] said that he learned guitar by listening to the albums McGeoch recorded with Siouxsie and the Banshees.<ref>Paytress, Mark. ''Siouxsie & the Banshees: The Authorised Biography''. Sanctuary, 2003. {{ISBN|1-86074-375-7}}</ref> [[John Frusciante]] of [[Red Hot Chili Peppers]] named McGeoch in his primary influences: \"[McGeoch] is such a guitarist I aspire to be. He has a new brilliant idea for each song. I usually play on the stuff he does on Magazine's albums and Siouxsie & the Banshees's like ''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]''\".<ref>{{cite news|author=Tore S Borjesson |url=http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/musik/article10360246.ab |title=Red Hots verkliga frontman John Frusciante |newspaper=Aftonbladet |date=24 April 2003 |accessdate=2 July 2016 |url-status=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703193605/http://www.aftonbladet.se/nojesbladet/musik/article10360246.ab |archivedate=3 July 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2008, the BBC aired an hour-long radio documentary on McGeoch's life and work, titled ''Spellbound: The John McGeoch Story''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rAoLW3Mdt4o |title='Spellbound: The John McGeoch Story' \u2013 hour-long BBC radio documentary |publisher=[[YouTube]] |accessdate=2014-07-15}}</ref>\n\n==Equipment==\nDuring his time with Magazine McGeoch played a [[Yamaha Corporation|Yamaha]] SG1000 guitar with a stand-mounted [[MXR]] M117R [[flanging|flanger]].<ref>[http://www.wire-sound.com/2008/12/12/noko-ipso-facto-devoto/ Wire-sound.com, ''Magazine'', 12/12/2008] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090221042437/http://www.wire-sound.com/2008/12/12/noko-ipso-facto-devoto/ |date=21 February 2009 }}''With Magazine, McGeoch played a Yamaha SG1000 + MXR Flanger + a few other bits.''</ref> He bought his first model in 1976 when the band signed its recording deal, which provided him with the finances for professional standard equipment.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.armouryshow.com/media/interviews/1985-11-00_The_Guitarist-John_mcgeoch_01.jpg |title=Interview |website=Armourshow.com |accessdate=2013-06-17}}</ref> Whilst with Siouxsie and the Banshees he created his own setup, involving an MXR flanger mounted on a mic stand which allowed him to hit a chord and sweep the flange knob in real time.<ref>\"The Gothfather\" [Robert Smith of the Cure interview]. Guitar Word. June 1996</ref> Whilst working with 'The Armoury Show', he also used a [[Squier Stratocaster|Squier 1957 Stratocaster]] and an [[Ibanez]] AE410BK. During his work with PiL, and in his last years he favoured a solid wood [[Carvin Corporation|Carvin]] electric guitar.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://equipboard.com/pros/john-mcgeoch/carvin-dc400-electric-guitar|title=John McGeoch's Carvin DC400 Electric Guitar|website=Equipboard.com|accessdate=28 April 2019}}</ref> He also used a [[Washburn Guitars|Washburn]] Tour 24 guitar for touring during 1988.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5UGUjs_7cPA|title=Public Image Ltd.- Glasnost Rock- Rock Summer 1988|last=Miguel Martinez|date=8 January 2013|accessdate=28 April 2019|publisher=[[YouTube]]}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n;Magazine\n*''[[Real Life (Magazine album)|Real Life]]'' (1978)\n*''[[Secondhand Daylight]]'' (1979)\n*''[[The Correct Use of Soap]]'' (1980)\n;Visage\n*''[[Visage (Visage album)|Visage]]'' (1980)\n;Gen X\n*''[[Kiss Me Deadly (album)|Kiss Me Deadly]]'' (1981)\n;Siouxsie and the Banshees\n*''[[Kaleidoscope (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Kaleidoscope]]'' (1980)\n*''[[Juju (Siouxsie and the Banshees album)|Juju]]'' (1981)\n*''[[A Kiss in the Dreamhouse]]'' (1982)\n;The Armoury Show\n*''[[Waiting for the Floods]]'' (1985)\n;Peter Murphy\n*''[[Should the World Fail to Fall Apart]]'' (1986)\n;Public Image Ltd\n*''[[Happy? (Public Image Ltd. album)|Happy?]]'' (1987)\n*''[[9 (Public Image Ltd. album)|9]]'' (1989)\n*''[[That What Is Not]]'' (1992)\n;The Sugarcubes\n*''[[Stick Around for Joy]]'' (1992)\n\n==See also==\n*[[John Doyle (drummer)|John Doyle]]\n*[[Russell Webb (musician)|Russell Webb]]\n*[[Slik]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.fodderstompf.com/MEMBERS/mcgeoch.html Fodderstompf.Com: John McGeoch Biography]\n* [https://www.myspace.com/j_mcgeoch John McGeoch MySpace Account (set up by his daughter)]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051215185737/http://shotbybothsides.com/mag_john.htm Profile of John McGeoch from shotbybothsides.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20060102232625/http://shotbybothsides.com/zig_0284.htm Interview with John McGeoch from shotbybothsides.com]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20051215000007/http://america.net/~davdmock/armoury1.htm Interview with John McGeoch and Richard Jobson of Armoury Show]\n\n{{Magazine (band)}}\n{{Siouxsie and the Banshees}}\n{{Public Image Ltd}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McGeoch, John}}\n[[Category:1955 births]]\n[[Category:2004 deaths]]\n[[Category:Scottish rock guitarists]]\n[[Category:Male guitarists]]\n[[Category:Magazine (band) members]]\n[[Category:Siouxsie and the Banshees members]]\n[[Category:Public Image Ltd members]]\n[[Category:The Armoury Show members]]\n[[Category:Gothic rock musicians]]\n[[Category:Scottish new wave musicians]]\n[[Category:People from Greenock]]\n[[Category:20th-century guitarists]]\n", "name_user": "Freewheeling frankie", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEquipment:Changed 1976 to 1977 - Magazine formed in 1977 so, per his quote of \"1976-77\" in the referenced interview, he can't have bought that guitar in 1976.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_McGeoch"}
